Yes, virtual threads are an excellent choice for this scenario. Even though 2,000 records is a relatively small number for a modern JVM,
virtual threads provide a cleaner, more scalable way to handle the I/O-bound nature of API calls compared to traditional thread pools.
Here is a breakdown of why they fit this use case and how to think about "batching" in this new context.
Why Virtual Threads are a Good Fit
 * Simplified Blocking Code: You can write simple, synchronous code (e.g., using RestTemplate or HttpClient) for each API call. You don't need to learn complex reactive programming (Mono/Flux) to get high performance.
 * Resource Efficiency: 2,000 platform threads would consume roughly 2GB of RAM just for their stacks. 2,000 virtual threads consume only a few megabytes.
 * No Pool Tuning: You don't have to guess the "right" number of threads for a pool. The JVM handles the mounting/unmounting automatically when the API call waits for a response.
The Shift in "Batching" Strategy
In the past, "batching" often meant processing 50 records at a time because you only had 50 threads. With virtual threads,
you have two ways to approach this:
1. The "Hammer" Approach (Parallel Execution)
If the target API is internal or highly scalable, you can simply fire all 2,000 calls at once.
 * The Logic: Create 2,000 virtual threads. Each one handles one record.
 * The Benefit: Extreme simplicity.
2. The "Good Citizen" Approach (Throttled Execution)
If the target API has rate limits (e.g., 100 requests per second), you shouldn't fire all 2,000 at once. Instead of batching by thread count, you batch by concurrency limits using a Semaphore.
public void processRecords(List<Record> records) {
    // Limit to 50 concurrent API calls to avoid overwhelming the target system
    Semaphore limit = new Semaphore(50);

    try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
        for (Record record : records) {
            executor.submit(() -> {
                limit.acquire(); // Wait for a permit
                try {
                    callExternalApi(record);
                } finally {
                    limit.release(); // Release permit for the next thread
                }
                return null;
            });
        }
    } catch (Exception e) {
        // Handle errors
    }
}

Comparison: Virtual Threads vs. Alternatives
| Method | Effort | Scalability | Best For... |
|---|---|---|---|
| Platform Thread Pool | Medium | Limited by RAM/OS | Legacy apps with fixed capacity. |
| Reactive (WebFlux) | High | Very High | Extremely high-scale, non-blocking stacks. |
| Virtual Threads | Low | Very High | Most modern Java I/O tasks (API calls, DB). |
| Parallel Streams | Very Low | Poor for I/O | CPU-bound math/sorting only. |
Summary Checklist for your 2k Records:
 * Memory: No concern (2k virtual threads is tiny).
 * Database: If you fetch 2k records, do it in one query first, then iterate.
 * API Limits: This is your only real bottleneck. Use a Semaphore as shown above to keep the target system stable.
 * Error Handling: Use a try-catch inside the virtual thread task so one failed API call doesn't stop the other 1,999.
